Nassim Nicholas Taleb defines black swans as events that:

Are totally unpredictable by mortal minds. Have a disproportionately large impact. Have retroactive predictability imposed on them through the foresight of 20/20 hindsight.

Taleb frequently points to the outbreak of World War I as an example of a black swan. He scoffs at historical accounts that present the outbreak as the result of trends that built up over the preceding decades, dismissing
